# Code Style

Follows Linux kernel coding style (Documentation/process/coding-style.rst)
with minor adaptations for embedded/bare-metal context.

## Indentation
- **Tabs**, not spaces. Tab width = 8 characters.
- Continuation lines: align to opening parenthesis or indent one extra tab.

## Line Length
- Soft limit: **80 columns**. Hard limit: **100 columns**.
- Exceptions: strings, include paths, assembly operands.

## Braces
K&R style — opening brace on the same line as the statement, closing brace on its own line.

```c
/* functions: opening brace on its OWN line */
int ulmk_thread_yield(void)
{
	...
}

/* everything else: opening brace on SAME line */
if (cond) {
	...
} else {
	...
}

for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
	...
}
```

Single-statement bodies: **always** use braces.

## Spaces
- Space after keywords: `if (`, `for (`, `while (`, `switch (`
- No space between function name and `(`: `ulmk_thread_yield()`
- Space around binary operators: `a + b`, `x = y`
- No space inside parentheses: `(x + y)`, not `( x + y )`

## Naming
- Functions and variables: `snake_case`
- Macros and constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Typedefs: `snake_case_t`
- Public API: prefixed with module name — `ulmk_thread_*`, `ulmk_ep_*`, `ulmk_irq_*`
- Kernel-internal: no `ulmk_` prefix needed

## Comments
Prefer `/* */` over `//`. Block comments:

```c
/*
 * Multi-line comment describing non-obvious behaviour,
 * hardware quirks or design trade-offs.
 */
```

No comments that just narrate what the code does.

## Declarations
- One variable per line.
- Declare variables at the **top** of the block (C89 style, avoids confusion on deeply nested scopes).
- No unnecessary initialisation to zero when the first use assigns the value.

## Headers
- Each module has exactly one public header.
- Include guards: `#ifndef UL_FOO_H` / `#define UL_FOO_H` / `#endif`.
- Order: system headers (`<stdint.h>`, ...), then project headers.

## Typedefs
Use `typedef` only for:
- Opaque handles exposed in public API (`ulmk_ep_t`, `ulmk_tid_t`)
- Function pointer types (`ulmk_irq_handler_t`)
- Fixed-layout structs in public API (`ulmk_msg_t`, `ulmk_thread_attr_t`)

Do **not** typedef internal structs; use `struct foo` directly.
